## Workload and Job Demands

### Increased Job Demands and Emotional Labor

Staff, particularly faculty and admissions officers, report increased job demands, especially during peak periods such as reading seasons. Heavy workloads with limited flexibility contribute to job stress and emotional exhaustion, leading to turnover intentions ([Figueroa, 2015](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281269358_The_Influences_Impacting_Staff_Turnover_in_Higher_Education); [Pantazes, 2021](https://www.researchgate.net/publication/348846157_Other_Duties_as_Assigned_Turnover_and_Turnover_Intentions_among_Early_Career_Undergraduate_Admissions_Officers_at_Selective_Higher_Education_Institutions)).

Burnout is a critical factor linked to workload. It manifests as emotional exhaustion, depersonalization, and reduced personal accomplishment. Faculty with higher workloads, including teaching large numbers of students and extensive grading responsibilities, are more susceptible to burnout ([Lackritz, 2004](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tate.2004.07.002)).

### Burnout and Its Dimensions

- **Emotional Exhaustion:** Feeling drained and fatigued due to work demands.
- **Depersonalization:** Developing negative attitudes toward students or colleagues.
- **Reduced Personal Accomplishment:** Feeling ineffective or dissatisfied with achievements.

Approximately 20% of faculty experience high levels of burnout, with emotional exhaustion being more prevalent among female faculty, and depersonalization higher among male faculty ([Lackritz, 2004](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tate.2004.07.002)).

